# Commit and deploy after updates

The user authorizes committing without asking again when finishing meaningful work in this repo.

## When to commit

After edits that touch application code, config used in production, or assets referenced by the app:

1. Stage only intentional changes. Never stage `.env`, `.env.local`, `node_modules/`, `.next/`, or other ignored paths.
2. Prefer `npm run ship -- "type: short message"` when many files changed (it runs safety checks). For a small, explicit set, `git add <paths>` then `git commit` is fine.
3. Use clear messages, e.g. `feat:`, `fix:`, `chore:`, `style:`.

## Push and Vercel

This project’s GitHub default branch is **main**; work often lands on **master**. Vercel production follows **main**.

After pushing **master**, always run:

```bash
git push origin master:main
```

so production (e.g. dosantosmarket.vercel.app) receives the same commits.

## When not to commit

- Work is half-done or broken on purpose.
- Only local experiments or the user asked to hold changes.

If nothing changed in tracked files, skip commit.
